body:
When there is an assertion or a finish or fatal call in my Verilog, code, these get translated into call to either `VL_STOP_MT` or `VL_FINISH_MT. For example:

```.cpp
    if (VL_UNLIKELY(((IData)(vlTOPp->selParent) & (IData)(vlTOPp->stop0En)))) {
        VL_FINISH_MT("test.sv", 93, "");
    }
    if (VL_UNLIKELY(((IData)(vlTOPp->selParent) & (IData)(vlTOPp->stop1En)))) {
        VL_WRITEF("[%0t] %%Error: test.sv:104: Assertion failed in %Ntest\n",
                  64,VL_TIME_UNITED_Q(1),vlSymsp->name());
        VL_STOP_MT("test.sv", 104, "");
    }
```

The first two argument (`filename` and `linenum`) contain the expected values. However the third argument `hier` is always left blank. I was hoping that it would contain a hierarchical path in order to be able to know which instance of a module had the failing assertion. Was that the intention and it was just never implemented? Or am I misunderstanding the use of `hier`?

What 'verilator --version' are you using?  Did you try it with the git master version?

I tried it out with the version that comes with Fedora (`4.108`). I also tested the latest version from the [oss-cad-toolchain](https://github.com/YosysHQ/oss-cad-suite-build/releases) (`Verilator 4.213 devel rev v4.212-46-g20af8a36`) which also leaves `hier` blank.

Would you be willing to try to fix Verilator yourself with assistance?

If I understand correctly that `hier` should actually contain the hierarchical path, similar to what is already included in the error message (using `VL_WRITEF`), I could have a shot at fixing that.
